[SourceTitle "01 Introduction"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/7032108"]

{The opening is the first phase of a chess game and is where we have to decide 
how to activate our army. After just one move each there are already 400 
different possible positions, and after two moves each there are 71,852! Clearly 
it is impossible to learn every possibility and so like any other stage of the 
game we need some principles and ideas to help us play well. Many players rush 
the opening believing it to be unimportant. This is a mistake as games can be 
lost as early as move 2! The opening is a vital stage of a chess game and 
playing it well will significantly improve your results. In this course we 
explore the FOUR OPENING LAWS and their evil counterparts the FIVE DEADLY SINS. 
Mastering these concepts will enable us to consistently get good positions out 
of the opening whatever our opponents throw at us. We will also examine quick 
knockout blows and how to defend against premature attacks such as Scholar's 
Mate. Typical tactics and typical opening checkmates are explored in some depth 
before finishing with a final test to check your knowledge.} 1. -- *

[Event "Tournament Ready: The Opening"]
[Site "Opening Laws"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 - Opening Laws"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 Opening Laws"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291161"]

{In chess we say there are three main stages to a game: • 1) The Opening; • 
2) The Middlegame; • 3) The Endgame. The opening is the beginning of the game: 
the stage where both players are bringing their pieces into the action. It is 
important to play the opening well and by doing so this will set us up well for 
the rest of the game. Some games are even decided before the opening has 
finished. There are FOUR OPENING LAWS we want you to be aware of: • 1) 
Activate (Develop) your pieces (particularly your minor pieces - ie. Knights and 
Bishops); • 2) Control some of the central squares; • 3) Make sure your King 
is safe; • 4) Look out for traps and tactical opportunities (for both sides)! 
Unlike the real law - sometimes we are allowed to break the opening laws, but 
only if there is a very good reason and you understand why you are breaking it!} 
1. e4 {[%cal Gf1b5,Gd1h5][%csl Ge4,Gd5] A good first move (and the most 
popular): White grabs space and begins to control some central squares (Law 2) . 
It also frees up the Bishop and Queen to develop (Law 1).} a5 {Not a good move! 
This move has no logic behind it and doesn't follow any of the FOUR OPENING 
LAWS.} 2. d4 {[%cal Gd1d3,Gc1g5,Gf1b5,Gd1h5][%csl Gd4,Ge4,Ge5,Gd5] (Law 2) White 
now controls the centre and both Bishops are free to develop.} h5 {Black 
continues the policy of pointless moves!} 3. Nf3 {Bringing out a piece (Law 1).} 
Na6 {Bringing out a piece - but the edge of the board normally isn't a good 
square for the Knights as from there they don't control many important squares.} 
(3... Nc6 {In this position, developing towards the centre would allow White to 
attack the Knight and grab even more space and squares with} 4. d5 {.}) 4. Bc4 
{Bringing out another piece (Law 1) and preparing to castle.} Nh6 {Another piece 
on the side of the board.} 5. O-O {White castles the King away to safety (Law 
3). This also brings the Rook on h1 closer to the action in the centre of the 
board where lines are more likely to open up.} Ra7 {This doesn't really count as 
a 'developing move' as the Rook doesn't do anything active on a7. Black should 
be thining about how to get a foothold in the centre and develop the Bishops.} 
(5... e6 {is better;}) (5... d6 {is another alternative.}) 6. Nc3 {Developing 
the Knight towards the centre (Law 1) - normally a good idea.} Rg8 7. Bf4 {[%csl 
Ge4,Gf4,Gf3,Gd4,Gc4,Gc3,Gg1] White has brought out all of his 'minor pieces' 
(Knights and Bishops) and controls the central squares with his Pawns. The King 
is safely castled. White's next job is to begin to look for targets in the black 
camp to attack, but this is the next stage of the game... Look at the 
arrangement of the white pieces. This is often considered the ideal central 
setup. It is rare we can achieve this in a game as our opponents will try and 
stop this.} *

