the action in the centre.} (5. Bg5 {This is a good square for the Bishop, but we 
should try and avoid moving the same piece twice in the opening unless there is 
a very good reason to do so.}) *

[Event "Tournament Ready: The Opening"]
[Site "Activate your Pieces"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2 - Activate your Pieces"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "03 Activate your Pieces"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291165"]

{In chess we should always be aiming to activate our pieces. This means placing 
them on squares where they do a useful job, for example controlling a lot of 
squares or attacking a weak point in the opponent's camp. The opening is our 
first opportunity to activate our pieces and it is important we do this quickly. 
By bringing a piece off the back row and activating it we say it is 'developed'. 
For example we have 'developed the Bishop to c4 (from f1). We should normally 
develop our minor pieces (Knights and Bishops) before our Queen and Rooks - 
though this is a rule which can often be broken if you have a good reason! The 
most normal sequence of priorities in the opening goes something like this: • 
1) Pawn in the centre; • 2) Develop a Knight and Bishop to allow castling; • 
3) Castle; • 4) Develop the remaining minor pieces; • 5) Activate the Queen; 
• 6) Activate the Rooks.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 {This is called the Vienna Opening. 
Most opening sequences are given a name, either after the place it was first 
famously played or after the name of the player who first used it successfully.} 
Qh4 {Developing the Queen this early is rarely a good idea. White can easily 
defend against the threats and force the Queen back whilst developing his own 
pieces.} 3. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3h4] Developing a piece with tempo (i.e., whilst 
attacking a piece).} Qe7 {[%cal Ge7e5] Defending e5.} 4. Bc4 Nc6 5. O-O {It's 
normally a good idea to castle as early as possible!} h6 {Black may be worried 
about Ng5 ideas, but he is already 'behind in development' and this allows White 
to further increase his advantage.} 6. d4 {[%cal Gc1h6] Opening up the diagonal 
for the bishop and also lines for the Queen. It is good to open up the position 
when your opponent is several moves away from castling.} exd4 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. 
Qxd4 {White has brought his Queen out, but notice that it is quite safe and 
cannot be attacked by the enemy Knight.} d6 (8... c5 {This attacks the Queen but 
doesn't actually help Black in any way. In fact it just creates a big weakness 
on d5.}) 9. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e8] It is often a good idea to line up your Rook 
against the enemy Queen, especially when the King is on the same line as well!} 
Be6 10. Bf4 {White continues to bring all the pieces into the game.} Qd7 11. 
Rad1 {[%csl Gd1,Ge1,Gc3,Gc4,Gd4,Gf4,Rh8,Rg8,Rf8,Re8,Ra8] White now has every 
piece centralised and developed. Black has several pieces un-developed and the 
King is still stuck in the centre.} Nf6 {With all of White's pieces poised it is 
time to strike.} (11... O-O-O 12. Qxa7 {doesn't help Black.}) 12. e5 {Blasting 
open the centre.} dxe5 13. Qxe5 {[%cal Gd1d7] A discovered attack on the Queen.} 
Bd6 14. Qf5 {[%cal Gd1d7,Ge1e8][%csl Re6,Rd6] The Bishop on e6 is pinned and 
attacked three times but only defended twice. The other Bishop is also pinned!} 
O-O 15. Rxe6 {A temporary sacrifice.} fxe6 16. Bxe6+ {[%cal Ge6g8,Ge6d7][%csl 
Rd7] This fork will win the Queen and White should win the game. Black lost 
valuable time in the opening messing about with his Queen. White was able to 
build up a formidable lead in development and take advantage of this when the 
position was opened up.} *

