[White "3 - Control the Centre #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 Control the Centre"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291164"]

{The centre consists of the squares on e4, d4, d5 and e5. Generally it is 
considered good strategy to try and control these squares with our Pawns and 
pieces. In general it is a good idea to put one or more Pawns in the centre if 
given the opportunity: • 1) This allows us to develop our Bishop and Queen; 
• 2) This can push back the enemy forces; • 3) It creates a shield to stop 
the enemy pushing back our pieces.} 1. e4 {The most popular opening move, 
grabbing some of the centre and allowing the Bishop and Queen to develop.} g6 
{[%cal Gf8g7] Not a bad move but it is risky and you need to know how to handle 
the position accurately. This is known as 'The Modern Defence'.} 2. d4 {White 
puts a second Pawn in the centre. IF POSSIBLE AIM TO PUT TWO PAWNS ON THE 
CENTRAL SQUARES IF THEY CANNOT BE CAPTURED.} Bg7 3. Nf3 {Bringing out the Knight 
'towards' the centre.} Nf6 4. Nc3 Nc6 {[%csl Rd7,Re7,Ge4,Gd4] Both sides have 
brought out their Knights. However, the white pieces are supported by an 
impressive Pawn centre which is now able to force the black Knights back.} 5. e5 
Ng8 6. Bf4 {It is harder for Black to develop than it is for White due to 
White's greater central control.} d6 7. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5e8][%csl Rc6] Developing a 
piece and pinning Black's Knight.} dxe5 8. Nxe5 {[%cal Gb5c6,Ge5c6]} Bxe5 9. 
Bxe5 Nf6 {Developing a piece and blocking the attack on the Rook in the corner.} 
10. d5 {[%cal Gd5c6][%csl Rc6] Attacking the pinned piece.} a6 {Black hopes to 
chase away the pinner.} 11. Qf3 {White brings the Queen into the game and also 
aims to bring the Rook into play via d1.} (11. Ba4 b5 {is Black's idea.}) axb5 
12. dxc6 bxc6 13. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] Developing a piece 'with tempo' - this means 
to develop a piece whilst atacking an opponent's piece.} Bd7 {Although this 
moves the Bishop, it is very passive on d7 and just serves a defensive 
function.} 14. O-O {Castling to safety and bringing the other Rook into play.} 
O-O 15. Bxf6 exf6 16. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4c5,Ge4f6] White is attacking the Pawn on f6 
twice, but as we will see White also has another idea.} Kg7 17. Nc5 {[%cal 
Gc5d7,Gd1d8][%csl Rd7] Exploiting the pin on the Bishop by the Rook. White will 
now win material. The extra central control allowed White to develop faster and 
more aggressively which eventually led to the win of material through tactical 
means.} *

[Event "Tournament Ready: The Opening"]
[Site "Control the Centre"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3 - Control the Centre #2"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 Control the Centre"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291163"]

1. e4 e5 {Black also fights for the centre - a good response.} 2. Nf3 {[%cal 
Gf3e5][%csl Ge5] White attacks e5 and develops a piece.} (2. d4 {puts another 
Pawn in the centre, but this isn't always a good idea if the opponent can 
capture the Pawn - we have to weigh up every decision.} 2... exd4 3. Qxd4 Nc6 
{Black gains time attacking the white Queen. This is why this line isn't very 
popular for White.}) Nc6 {[%cal Rc6e5][%csl Re5] Black defends e5 and develops a 
piece.} 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 {[%cal Gc3d4,Gd2d4] A useful idea to remember. White 
wants to play d4 and recapture on d4 with a pawn to maintain a strong Pawn 
centre.} (4. d4 Bxd4 5. Nxd4 Nxd4 {loses a Pawn.}) Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 5. d4 
{Grabbing more of the centre and at the same time attacking the Bishop on c5.} 
exd4 6. cxd4 Bb6 {A bad move and a typical mistake. This is too defensive and 
Black should have given a check.} (6... Bb4+ {is the best move - the point is 
that the check gives Black some extra time to fight White's central control, for 
example:} 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 d5 {and this position is known to be fairly 
level.}) 7. e5 {White grabs more space and attacks the Knight.} Ng8 8. d5 
{Pushing Black even further back.} Nce7 9. d6 {And further!} cxd6 10. exd6 Nc6 
11. O-O {Castling not only makes White's King safe, but White intends to play 
Re1 check attacking the black King.} Nf6 12. Re1+ {Black cannot block the check 
without losing material so the King must step to the side. But this means that 
Black will never be able to castle and the King will be permanently weak (it 
will also make it hard for Black to activate the Rook on h8) .} Kf8 13. Nc3 
{[%csl Ra8,Rc8,Rh8] White continues to activate all his pieces. Notice how it is 
difficult for Black to develop his pieces - particularly both Rooks and the 
Bishop on c8.} a6 14. Bg5 Ba7 {White has brought most of the pieces to their 
logical squares and now begins to attack targets in the black position.} 15. Nd5 
{This exploits the pin on the Knight.} b5 16. Nxf6 gxf6 (16... bxc4 17. Nxh7+ 
{Discovered check.} Rxh7 18. Bxd8 {This wins material.}) 17. Bh6+ Kg8 18. Nd4 
{[%cal Gd1g4,Gg4g8] Threatening a deadly check on g4.} f5 19. Bxf7+ {This 
'sacrifice forces checkmate'.} Kxf7 20. Qh5+ Kg8 (20... Kf6 21. Qxf5#) 21. Re8+ 
Qxe8 22. Qxe8# {White's attack was unstoppable - but it all stemmed from the 
fact that White had complete control of the centre and was able to push back the 
black pieces.} *

