[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291187"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 Bc5 3. Nf3 exf4 {How should White proceed?} 4. d4 {[%cal 
Gd4c5][%csl Gd4,Ge4,Rc5] Grabbing the centre and attacking the Bishop.} Bd6 
{[%cal Gd6f4]} 5. e5 {[%cal Ge5d6][%csl Rd6]} Be7 6. Bxf4 *

[Event "Tournament Ready: The Opening"]
[Site "King Safety"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4 - King Safety #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 King Safety"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291168"]

{The following game was played in 1910. The player with the white pieces was the 
very strong master Aron Nimzowitsch.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 {Developing a piece and 
attacking a Pawn.} Nc6 {Developing a piece and defending the e5-Pawn.} 3. Bb5 
{Developing the Bishop and attacking the defender of the e5-Pawn.} Nf6 4. O-O d6 
{[%csl Rf8] Solid but a bit passive, as the Bishop on f8 is now restricted to 
the e7-square.} (4... Nxe4 {is possible when White has two popular 
alternatives:} 5. Re1 ({and} 5. d4 {.})) 5. d4 {[%cal Gc1g5] A typical freeing 
move.} Nxe4 {As is often the case, this Pawn grab turns out to be a mistake.} 6. 
d5 {[%cal Gb5e8][%csl Rc6] Attacking the pinned Knight.} a6 7. Bd3 {[%cal 
Gd3e4,Gd5c6][%csl Gc6,Ge4] White is attacking both Knights.} (7. Ba4 b5 {This 
counter-attack would break the pin and leave Black with a good game.}) Nf6 8. 
dxc6 e4 {[%cal Ge4d3,Ge4f3] Black was relying on this fork.} 9. Re1 {[%cal 
Ge1e8][%csl Re4] Pinning the Pawn against the King. This is a very typical 
problem when you haven't castled - the King can be vulnerable to a Rook or Queen 
on the open file.} d5 10. Be2 {Setting a trap.} exf3 {And Black falls into it!} 
(10... bxc6 {was necessary.} 11. Nfd2 Bd6 {and Black has some play for the 
missing Knight.}) 11. cxb7 Bxb7 (11... fxe2 12. bxa8=Q {White takes a Rook and 
gains a new Queen (a gain of 13 points in just one move)! Black cannot capture 
the Queen with the Pawn as it is pinned.}) 12. Bb5# {Double checkmate mate - the 
game is over immediately! A very clear example of the dangers of leaving the 
King in the middle for too long.} *

[Event "Tournament Ready: The Opening"]
[Site "King Safety"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4 - King Safety #2"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 King Safety"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291167"]

{The following is a famous game by the American legend Paul Morphy. This game 
was played in Paris in 1958 and is a great example of the dangers of not 
castling - and also the power of fast development.} 1. e4 {Rule 2 - control the 
centre.} e5 2. Nf3 {Rule 1 - activate your pieces. This move is very good as it 
brings out the Knight to a central square and attacks the Pawn on e5.} d6 
{Defending the Pawn and preparing to bring out the Bishop.} 3. d4 {[%cal 
Gc1g5,Gd1d3] Freeing up more space for the pieces.} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1][%csl Rf3] 
Pinning the Knight and avoiding the loss of a Pawn.} (3... exd4 {is better.}) 4. 
dxe5 Bxf3 (4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Nxe5 {and White has won a Pawn.}) 5. Qxf3 
dxe5 6. Bc4 {[%cal Gf3f7] Developing a piece and threatening checkmate.} Nf6 
{Blocking the checkmate.} 7. Qb3 {[%csl Gf7,Gb7] Although you should be careful 
about moving the Queen too many times in the opening, rule 4 is also important. 
Look out for opportunities and targets in the opponent's camp. Here Morphy 
noticed that f7 and b7 could both be attacked by the Queen.} Qe7 (7... b6 
{defends the b7 Pawn but would allow checkmate in 2 moves:} 8. Bxf7+ Kd7 9. 
Qe6#) 8. Nc3 {Developing another piece.} (8. Qxb7 Qb4+ 9. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 10. c3 {is 
a safe extra Pawn for White, but Morphy wanted more.}) c6 {[%cal Ge7b7] 
Defending b7.} 9. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5e7][%csl Rf6] Developing with a pin.} b5 {Black 
tries to force the Bishop back but now White has a powerful sacrifice.} 10. Nxb5 
cxb5 11. Bxb5+ {White has given up a Knight for two Pawns but the black King is 
caught in the centre and his position is a disaster.} Nbd7 12. O-O-O {[%cal 
Gd1d7,Gb5e8][%csl Rd7] Castling whilst attacking the Knight on d7. Notice how 
one of the defenders is pinned (the Knight on f6) .} Rd8 {Defending d7, but 
White can crash through by bringing in the final piece - the Rook on h1!} 13. 
Rxd7 Rxd7 14. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d7,Gb5e8][%csl Rd7] Black is powerless to defend d7. 
Look at the useless Bishop on f8 and Rook on h8 - how Black would love to be 
able to castle here!} Qe6 {Stepping out of the pin but allowing a very famous 
finish.} 15. Bxd7+ Nxd7 16. Qb8+ {A Queen sacrifice leading to checkmate!} Nxb8 
17. Rd8# {[%cal Gg5d8] White combined fast development with threats to keep 
Black in a defensive posture. Black wasn't given time to develop properly and 
castle the King to safety. In the end the King perished in the centre of the 
board!} *

