[Event "Tournament Ready: The Opening"]
[Site "Five Deadly Sins"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5 - Five Deadly Sins"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "06 Five Deadly Sins"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291166"]

{We have discussed what we should be aiming to do in the opening. How about the 
things we should try and avoid? The following are five deadly sins of the 
opening. • 1) Not developing your Knights and Bishops; • 2) Moving the same 
piece more than once; • 3) Moving the Queen around too early; • 4) Keeping 
the King in the middle; • 5) Grabbing Pawns without considering the 
consequences. In the following game Black does everything wrong and gets 
punished quickly.} 1. e4 e5 {This is the last good move Black makes!} 2. Nf3 
{Developing a piece and attacking the Pawn on e5} Qf6 {This is Deadly Sin number 
3. Black defends the Pawn but Queen will be exposed out in the open and White 
can gain time attacking her.} 3. Bc4 Qg6 {[%cal Gg6e4,Gg6g2][%csl Gg2,Ge4] Black 
attacks two Pawns but is making more Deadly Sins: still moving the queen around 
(sin 3), moving the same piece more than once (sin 2), not developing minor 
pieces (sin 1) and not getting any closer to castling (sin 4) .} 4. O-O {White 
has done everything right: Pawn in the centre, rapidly developed Knight and 
Bishop and a castled King. As we will see White is not concerned at all about 
the e4-Pawn.} Qxe4 {And finally Black commits the 5th sin - grabbing a Pawn 
without considering the consequences.} 5. Bxf7+ Ke7 {[%cal Rf3g5,Gg5e4,Gg5f7]} 
(5... Kxf7 6. Ng5+ {White would fork the Queen and King.}) (5... Kd8 {is 
slightly more resilient but White is so far ahead in development that he should 
be winning after most moves, such as} 6. d4) 6. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e7] Rooks belong 
on open files - especially when the enemy King is on that file!} Qf4 7. Bxg8 
Rxg8 8. d4 {[%cal Gc1f4] A discovered attack on the Queen.} Qf7 9. Bg5+ 
{Developing with a check.} Ke8 10. Nxe5 {[%cal Ge1e8] Attacking the Queen and 
opening up the file against the King.} Qd5 11. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5] Bringing out 
another piece and attacking the Queen. At this stage all moves win for White (!) 
but playing the most natural moves is often a good idea.} Qa5 12. Qf3 {[%cal 
Gf3f7][%csl Gf7] Threatening checkmate on f7. Black cannot defend.} Be7 13. Qf7+ 
Kd8 14. Bxe7# {[%csl Rc8,Rb8,Ra8] The black Queen managed to move seven times 
whereas Black's entire Queenside never moved at all. You cannot hope to be 
successful using just part of your army against a skilled player. All of your 
pieces need to be taking part. Try not to commit the deadly sins in your games 
or else you might end up on the receiving end like this!} *

