[SourceTitle "07 Defending against Scholar's Mate"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291169"]

{Let's look at a very well known opening trick - Scholar's Mate. Scholar's Mate 
is probably the most common of all opening traps amongst beginners, and many 
games are decided by this trap when the side defending does not smell a rat.} 1. 
e4 e5 2. Bc4 Bc5 3. Qh5 {[%cal Gh5f7] Threatening Qxf7 Scholar's Mate. Far too 
many games end this way and it is important you know how to defend.} Qf6 {[%cal 
Gf6f7] PROTECTING f7. This is perhaps the best way to defend: Black also 
counter-attacks against f2. Although bringing out the Queen this early is one of 
the deadly sins, here it is justified as we simply have to defend against the 
checkmate threat.} (3... g6 {BLOCKING the Queen from f7. However here there is a 
big problem with this move:} 4. Qxe5+ {White forks Black's king and rook.} 4... 
Qe7 (4... Be7 5. Qxh8 {White has won a Rook. Some games have finished as 
follows:} 5... Nc6 6. Qxg8+ Bf8 7. d4 (7. Qxf7 {would already be mate.}) Nxd4 8. 
Bh6 Nxc2+ 9. Kd1 Nxa1 10. Qxf8#) 5. Qxh8 {White has won a Rook. Some games have 
continued in the following way:} 5... Kf8 6. d4 Bxd4 7. Bh6+ {The Knight is 
pinned.} 7... Ke8 8. Qxg8+ Qf8 9. Qxf8#) (3... Nc6 {This just ignores the threat 
completely!} 4. Qxf7#) (3... Qe7 {PROTECTING f7. This is another good way to 
defend against the threat. A possible continuation is} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {Developing a 
piece and attacking the Queen.} 5. Qh3 {Not a good square for the Queen as could 
be vulnerable to a discovered attack from the c8-Bishop.} 5... Nc6 6. d3 d5 
{This discovered attack will win the Bishop on c4.}) (3... Nh6 {'knights on the 
rim are dim'. This move PROTECTS f7 but is bad due to the following move:} 4. d4 
{A discovered attack on the Knight.} 4... Bxd4 5. Bxh6 gxh6 6. Qxf7#) *

