[Event "Tournament Ready: The Opening"]
[Site "The Fried Liver Attack"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7 - Fried Liver Attack"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "08 The Fried Liver Attack"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291200"]

{Now we turn our attention to a very popular form of attack where White's Knight 
and Bishop attempt to gang up on Black's f7-Pawn. This is known in some quarters 
as the 'Fried Liver Attack'. Normally this name is only used for a particular 
variation of the attack but for simplicity we are going to use it to describe 
the general concept of the attack in the opening.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 
Bc5 {[%cal Gd8g5] This simple developing move is probably the easiest to 
remember when you are starting out and we recommend this move for your first few 
tournaments. The reason is that our Queen still controls the g5-square meaning 
white shouldn't play Ng5 next (though sometimes they do anyway)!} (3... Nf6 
{'The 2 Knights Defence'. This is a somewhat sharper alternative and Black is 
required to know some more 'book' moves.} 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 (5... Nxd5 
{isn't as strong:} 6. Nxf7 {This interesting sacrifice is the 'proper' Fried 
Liver variation.} (6. d4 {is established as the best move. White has a dangerous 
attack but Black is still in the game.}) 6... Kxf7 7. Qf3+ {Forking Knight and 
King. To hang on to the extra material the King must come forward.} 7... Ke6 8. 
Nc3 {Exploiting the pin to gang up on the Knight. Black must defend the Knight.} 
8... Ncb4 {Defending the Knight and threatening a fork on c2. The position is 
extremely complicated but we wouldn't recommend going down this route as Black 
as it is just too risky to play with a King on e6.}) 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 
{and now White has several alternatives which are all very interesting. White is 
a Pawn up but Black is active and will start to push back the white pieces. 
Further study of this position is outside the scope of this course.}) 4. d3 
{[%cal Gc1g5] Controlling the g5-square.} (4. Ng5 {The 'Drunken Fried Liver 
Attack'. This move is a terrible mistake - yet quite a common one. White attacks 
f7 not realising that the Knight can be taken!} 4... Qxg5 {Loose pieces drop 
off!} 5. d4 {A discovered attack on the Queen - but it doesn't work.} 5... Qxg2 
6. Rf1 Qxe4+ {Black is winning.}) Nf6 {Simple development is often best.} 5. Ng5 
{[%cal Gc4f7,Gg5f7] The 'Lame Fried Liver Attack'. All you need to remember here 
is that if you can castle then these attacks are harmless.} O-O {Black castles. 
But what happens now if White takes on f7?} 6. Nxf7 Rxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 {[%csl 
Gc6,Gc5,Gf6,Ra1,Rb1,Rc1,Rd1,Rh1] Black has taken a Knight and Bishop (6 points) 
but lost a Rook and a Pawn (6 points). But whilst material is level, Black is 
actually much better in this position, simply because his pieces are much more 
active than White's. Generally these type of trades favour the side gaining the 
two minor pieces unless the Rook is very active. But here it clearly isn't. The 
black King is perfectly safe and can retreat back to g8 at any moment.} *

