{Loose pieces drop off is a little saying to remind us that undefended pieces 
are vulnerable to capture, or to a tactical trick such as a fork. If our 
opponent offers us a free piece in the opening we should first check whether it 
is a trap and what would happen if we were to take the piece. But if we can't 
see any reason why not, then take the piece and win the game!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 
Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. Ng5 {For some reason this is a surprisingly common mistake. 
White is going for the Fried Liver attack but seems to be unaware that the 
g5-square is guarded by the Queen!} Qxg5 {Loose pieces drop off! A piece up, 
Black should win the game.} *

