[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291220"]

{One has to be extra-cautious about adventuring with the Queen early in the 
game. There is a very good reason that making too many moves with the Queen is 
one of the Deadly Sins! The Queen may often find herself getting trapped. The 
following is a game played in Paris, 1888 between Frazer and Taubenhaus.} 1. e4 
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 {The Scotch Opening.} exd4 4. Nxd4 Qh4 {This move is 
considered very risky.} 5. Nc3 Nf6 {This is already a big mistake as the Queen 
is deprived of retreat squares.} (5... Bb4 {is the best move according to 
'opening theory'.}) 6. Nf5 Qh5 (6... Qg4 {was the only move to stay in the 
game.} 7. f3 Qg6 8. Nb5 Kd8 9. Bf4 {With a huge advantage for White.}) 7. Be2 
Qg6 8. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4g6][%csl Rf5,Re4,Rg5,Rh5,Rh6,Rg4,Rg3,Rg2] The Queen is 
attacked and all the escapes squares are guarded. Black resigned!} *

