[SourceTitle "13 Deadly Checks"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291222"]

{At all stages of the game we should be on the lookout for FORCING MOVES: • 1) 
Checks; • 2) Captures; • 3) Threats. Checks in the opening can be 
particularly destructive if combined with a tactical device such as a fork or 
discovered attack. Or sometimes the King is so weak that a check may lead to 
checkmate. So always be on the lookout for checks in the opening. THAT DOES NOT 
MEAN GIVE A CHECK WHENEVER YOU CAN! It just means to stay alert to see if a 
check might be deadly or not. The following game was played in Buxton, 1950, 
between Veitch and Penrose (a 10-time British Champion, though at the time of 
this game he was only 17).} 1. e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine Defence.} 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 
{This defence is very risky for Black - he lures forward the white Pawns hoping 
to counter-attack later on.} Nb6 4. d4 d6 5. Bd3 {This is a poor move which goes 
unpunished.} dxe5 6. dxe5 N8d7 {A strange decision which puts Black on the brink 
of defeat!} (6... Nc6 {is much more natural and Black would have a very pleasant 
game after} 7. Nf3 Bg4) 7. e6 {A good Pawn sacrifice.} Nf6 {The losing move.} 
(7... Ne5 {was the only move to stay in the game as then Black can recapture on 
f7 with the Knight.} 8. exf7+ Nxf7 9. Nf3 {White has the better position but 
Black is still fighting.}) (7... fxe6 {White can now give a deadly check which 
leads to checkmate.} 8. Qh5+ g6 9. Bxg6+ (9. Qxg6+ {is somewhat flashier and 
also leads to checkmate:} 9... hxg6 10. Bxg6#) 9... hxg6 10. Qxg6#) 8. exf7+ 
Kxf7 {[%cal Gd1d8][%csl Rd3]} (8... Kd7 9. Bf5+ {Double check!} Kc6 10. Qxd8 
{also wins the Queen.}) 9. Bg6+ {[%cal Gd1d8,Gg6f7][%csl Rd8,Rf7] A deadly check 
and discovered attack on the Queen. Here Black resigned as he is losing a Queen 
for a Bishop.} hxg6 10. Qxd8 *

