[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "tournament-ready-the-opening/course/33414, variation/6291219"]

{It is possible for a game of chess to end very early, but only if a player 
makes some serious mistakes. Examples of mistakes include: • 1) Weakening the 
King unnecessarily, particularly moving the f-pawn; • 2) Not paying attention 
to the opponent's threats; • 3) Also commiting one or more of the opening 
deadly sins could put our King in mortal danger.} 1. d4 f5 {The Dutch Defence. A 
sound but risky opening.} 2. Bg5 {This move tempts Black to start chasing the 
Bishop, but Black should be careful about moving more Pawns around his King as 
the e8-h5 diagonal is potentially very weak.} h6 {[%cal Gh5e8]} 3. Bf4 g5 4. Bg3 
f4 {This is a mistake. Black believes he has trapped the white Bishop.} 5. e3 
{[%cal Gd1h5] Threatening Qh5 checkmate!} h5 {[%cal Gh8h5] Black is now 
defending h5 with the Rook, but White attacks from another angle...} 6. Bd3 
{[%cal Gd3g6] Developing a piece and threatening checkmate on g6.} Rh6 {This 
defends g6 - but only for one move.} (6... d5 {was the best defence and Black 
would still be in the game (just):} 7. exf4 h4 8. Bg6+ Kd7 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. Nxg5 
hxg3 11. Qg4+ Kc6 12. Qxg3 {White has three Pawns for the Bishop and many 
threats.}) 7. Qxh5+ {A spectacular Queen sacrifice and an example of 'removing 
the defence', ie. White is luring away the Rook from protecting g6.} Rxh5 8. 
Bg6# *

